
Section VII: Electronic Lab Book

7.1. Keeping Records

Reproducibility is extremely important to all scientific experiments, and computational chemistry is no exception. Just like any other chemistry lab it is useful to keep track of what you are doing during the course of an experiment, not simply at the end. The electronic nature of this field naturally lends itself to using an electronic lab book. There are many ways to keep a record of your work, depending on your familiarity with, and availability of, various programs. This section of the manual will describe a few ways to effectively keep track of your work.

7.1.1. Maintaining Directories

The first step in keeping good records is using a straight-forward and efficient filing system. An example directory schematic is shown in Figure 30 for a system involving multiple structures and types of calculations.

![](data:image/tiff;base64,)

Figure 30. Example directory layout for a question involving optimizations, frequencies and single-point energies on reactants, transition states and products of two reactions.

Let us examine the above layout and explain why this is an efficient model.

- All of the directory names involve lower case letters. LINUX is case sensitive, it is therefore faster to avoid using the SHIFT key.
- All the subdirectories begin with a different letter. In Linux, you only need to type enough of a file name to be unique; tapping the TAB key will fill in as much of the name as possible. In the above example, once in the lab1-q1 directory typing 'cd a' followed by TAB will fill in 'cd a-rxn1'.
- The final level of directories is used for storing completed files, which means that the calculations are run in the next level up. This is an efficient way to submit files, since it allows you to use wildcards to submit multiple files. For example, once the optimization files for the reactant, transition state and product complexes have been generated they are transferred to the a-rxn1 directory. From there, all the files are submitted together 'g09submit -wt 4h \*-o.com'. Once the calculations have finished running, and the .log files have been transferred back to your P: drive, move the files to structure specific directories using 'mv react-o.\* react-ofs'.
- Information on a specific structure can be quickly and easily found, since it is all together in one place.

7.1.2. Calculation Titles

The next way to keep track of your calculations is through proper titles in the command files. You should be able to know what a specific file is without having to open it in a viewing program.

Information that might be included in the title:

- The molecule name. While you can get the empirical formula from a .com and .log files, this does not include connectivity.
- If the setup for a file is complicated, you may want to include this information.
- What kind of calculation you are running and _why_.

7.1.3. Keeping Track of Data

The most important method for keeping track of your calculations is through Excel. This program can be used not only to calculate relative energies and make tables, but to monitor computational resources.

The following information should be kept for each group of calculations:

- Location where the files are saved on both the Windows and LINUX boxes.
- Description of what calculations are being recorded in that spreadsheet
- Level of theory the calculations were run at
- Zero-point scaling factor(s) if necessary

For each calculation you should keep track of:

- The name of the file
  - This is very important in the event that you need to double check an entry.
  - If you are using -o, -f and -s at the end of your file names to distinguish between optimization, frequency and single-point energy calculations, then you likely only need to keep track of the first portion of name.
- Resources used:
  - CPU time (from the .log)
  - Running time (from the .gstdout, used to predict walltime)
  - Memory requested
- Nature of the stationary point (minimum, transition state)
- Any required _raw_ energies, energy corrections, vibrational frequencies, bond lengths etc.
- Any required _relative_ energies
  - Make sure to keep track of units.
  - You may want to include a cell describing the formula used.

You may find it useful to have a file, either with Excel, Word, OneNote etc. to keep track of the status of your calculations (generated, submitted, data checked).

It is recommended that you spend some time becoming familiar with the different features of this powerful program.

![](data:image/png;base64,)Some features that you may find useful include:

**Conditional Formatting** (Home tab)

With conditional formatting you can have Excel automatically format cells based on their contents.

- Color Scales can be used to shade cells based on value, which is useful for finding the lowest energy without calculating relative energies.
- Highlight Cells Rules can be used to have Excel highlight any values that fit your criteria. For example, highlight bond lengths less than 2.1 .

**Text to Columns** (Data tab)

Use this for converting text into individual cells. You can use this to move energies from LINUX quickly.

**Selection Expansion**

![](data:image/png;base64,)A quick way to expand a formula is to select the cell and pull the selection using the square in the bottom right corner of the selected cell(s). When the example on the right is expanded down, it will fill in new cells with 8, 10, 12, etc.

If the contents of the copied cells contain references to other cells (such as in a formula) the reference will be altered according to the direction the cell is copied. If the cell is copied down, then the row will be changed. If you want to the reference to be maintained, use \$ to freeze the column, row, or both. For example, '=B4+\$A\$2' when copied downward would yield '=B5+\$A\$2'.

7.2. Summarizing Data

7.2.1. Tables

If you are using Excel to keep track of your data, you will likely find it easier to generate your tables in Excel rather than in Word.

A good table should have:

- A descriptive title that explains what is in the table and why it is important.
- Good column headers, including units.
- Numerical values should be to the correct significant figures (Section 9.2).
- The level of theory, which can be reported in the title or as a footnote.
- Unless specifically asked, do not report raw energies, only relative energies.

7.2.2. Graphs

Graphs can often be a useful tool in displaying data.

A good graph should include:

- A descriptive title that explains what the reader is supposed to take away from it.
  - X versus Y is NEVER a good title.
- Axis titles with units.
- Axis should be to the correct significant figures and have a small enough increment for a reader to determine important information.
- A legend if necessary.
- Markers and lines should be clear and legible when printed in black and white.
- Level of theory (energy//optimization if different).
- If you include a line of best fit always use linear regression (straight line), place the calculated quantity on the X-axis and the quantity you are trying to predict on the Y-axis.

7.2.3. Figures

Often, the simplest way to describe bond lengths and angles is to include a figure with these values annotated on the figure.

In GaussView, an image can be saved by using CTRL+I, or selecting Save Image from the File menu (there is a checkbox for a white background). The annotations can be added in another program, such as Paint, PowerPoint or Word.

In HyperChem, annotations can be added directly to the Workspace before saving an image. F9 will copy an image of the workspace to the clipboard.

In PyMol (either open-source or supported platforms), typing the ray command can be used to generate images (e.g., ray 1000 1000) will generate a 1000 pixel by 1000 pixel image.

A figure should have a caption associated with it that contains the following information:

- Level of theory (energy//optimization if energies reported),
- Units of any values reported in the annotation,
- What molecule(s) is(are) presented in the figure,
- Any other important information.
